🟦 1) What is Orchestration? (SUPER SIMPLE)

Orchestration = controlling the flow of steps.

If a pipeline is:

Step 1 → Step 2 → Step 3

Orchestration controls:

	•	When to run each step

	•	What input flows into each step

	•	When to call a tool

	•	When to call RAG

	•	When to call LLM

	•	When to stop

	•	When to branch

	•	When to retry

	•	When to skip a step

	•	How to passing state from one step to next

Think of it like a manager directing workers.

⸻

🟦 2) Why do we need orchestration?

Because real AI systems are not simple “input → output”.

Real business workflows have:

	•	conditional logic

	•	branching

	•	multiple tools

	•	validations

	•	retries

	•	error handling

	•	multiple LLM calls

	•	multi-step rules

Example underwriting workflow:

Extract data

IF score < 600 → reject

ELSE → Validate fields

IF missing fields → ask user

ELSE → Generate JSON

Upload to Blob

Notify user

LLMs alone cannot orchestrate this.

Pipelines alone cannot branch.

Agents alone cannot enforce strict sequence.

Orchestration solves this.

⸻

🟦 3) How LangChain performs orchestration

LangChain uses LCEL (LangChain Expression Language) to orchestrate steps.

The operator | pipes steps:

input | step1 | step2 | step3

Each step is a Runnable.

Orchestration in LangChain includes:

	•	Sequential flow (pipeline)

	•	Passing state between steps

	•	Mapping (dict-based orchestration)

	•	Branching (simple conditionals)

	•	Tool orchestration inside pipelines

	•	Error handling (retry wrappers)

	•	Parallel execution (RunnableParallel)

But LangChain cannot do:

	•	complex loops

	•	multi-agent coordination

	•	graph-like workflows

That’s where LangGraph comes later.

⸻

🟦 4) LCEL orchestration pattern

LangChain orchestration looks like:

step1 | step2 | step3

or more advanced:

{

  "a": step1,

  "b": step2

}

| step3

or with condition:

conditional_runnable = step1.branch(

    condition_fn,

    if_true=step2,

    if_false=step3

)


⸻

🟦 5) Types of orchestration in LangChain

1. Sequential orchestration

Straight pipeline:

A → B → C → D

2. Mapping orchestration (dict-based)

{

  "extraction": extractor,

  "validation": validator

}

→ formatter

3. Conditional orchestration

IF / ELSE logic inside the pipeline.

4. Parallel orchestration

Run multiple steps at the same time.

5. Retry orchestration

Retry LLM/tool automatically on failure.

6. Tool orchestration

Based on input → decide which tool to call.

These give you MOST of the power needed for enterprise usage.

⸻

🟦 6) Let’s build a real Orchestration workflow

We’ll build a workflow that:

	1.	Cleans input

	2.	Extracts age

	3.	If age < 18 → rejects

	4.	Else → approves

	5.	Formats output

A real underwriting-like flow.

